"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605481","Department for Education","false","2016-10-28","<p>Data on apprenticeship starts by framework for the 2002/03 to 2015/16 (full year provisional) academic years is given in the attached document.</p><p> </p><p>Apprenticeship data is not available by industry. Within an industry, a learner may undertake a wide range of apprenticeship frameworks.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-10-28T11:08:48.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605481/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605481/answer","HL2401_ attachment_data_on_apprenticeship_starts_by_framework.xlsx","HL2401_ attachment_data_on_apprenticeship_starts_by_framework.xlsx","Apprenticeship Starts by Framework","Apprenticeship Starts by Framework","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605481/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-18","Aerospace Industry: Apprentices","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many apprenticeships are currently in place in the UK aerospace industry.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones",,"Lord Jones","HL2401"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605482","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-01","<p>The Government is committed to getting the best possible deal for the UK financial services sector following the UK's departure from the EU.</p><p> </p><p>The insurance sector is diverse and the Government recognises that many firms are focused on domestic markets only. However, the Government understands that EU market access is important to the London Market, a leading global centre of expertise for specialist and commercial insurance, which provides valuable services to businesses in the EU and internationally.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has already engaged with international insurance and reinsurance companies and other key stakeholders in the insurance sector, and will continue to do so over the coming weeks and months. We are carefully analysing the impacts that withdrawal from the EU will have on their businesses, consumers and on other related economic activities. We will listen to concerns, aim to limit uncertainty in the transition and ensure our new relationship with the EU works for such businesses.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2016-11-01T13:14:27.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605482/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605482/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605482/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-18","Insurance Companies: Greater London","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have made an assessment of the impact of the potential loss of EU passporting rights on the international insurance and reinsurance companies operating in London, following the UK's departure from the EU.","true","Biography information for The Earl of Kinnoull",,"The Earl of Kinnoull","HL2402"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605483","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-25","<p>Implementation of the Energy Savings Opportunity Scheme remains an Environment Agency priority and there has been no change to the amount of resource assigned to this or to the level of oversight within the Agency.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-10-25T11:27:50.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605483/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605483/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605483/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-18","Energy: Conservation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps the Environment Agency is taking to ensure that decisions relating to the Energy Savings Opportunity Scheme receive director-level attention and remain adequately staffed.","false","Biography information for Lord Teverson",,"Lord Teverson","HL2403"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605484","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-24","<p>Since its inception in 2001, the Energy Technology List has incentivised UK businesses to invest in highly efficient plant and machinery as part of the Enhanced Capital Allowance Scheme, which provides a cash-flow advantage for businesses. Going forward, the Government will work to ensure that the Energy Technology List continues to help deliver our business energy-efficiency policy ambitions effectively whilst providing good value for money for tax payers.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-10-24T16:45:10.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605484/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605484/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605484/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-18","Energy: Conservation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have for the future of the Energy Technology List and the associated ability to claim Enhanced Capital Allowances.","false","Biography information for Lord Teverson",,"Lord Teverson","HL2404"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605485","Home Office","false","2016-11-22","<p>There remains no limit on the number of genuine international students who can come to study in the UK and visa applications from international students to study at British universities are up by 14% since 2010.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-11-22T13:00:12.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605485/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605485/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605485/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-18","Overseas Students","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of Home Office research indicating that only one per cent of foreign students fail to leave the country once they have completed their course, whether they intend to encourage more such students to study in the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Teverson",,"Lord Teverson","HL2405"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605486","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-10-31","<p>This Government understands the concept of parity of esteem, as set out in the 1998 Belfast Agreement, as placing a general obligation on the UK Government to govern in the interests of the whole community and to treat people of different traditions fairly and with equal respect. In the Agreement it is clearly expressed and defined in relation to people living in Northern Ireland. As a general obligation there is no definition of particular circumstances in which it does or does not apply.</p><p> </p><p>The concept of parity of esteem does not absolve people from upholding the law: terrorism was wholly wrong. This Government will never accept any form of equivalence between members of the armed forces who upheld democracy and the rule of law and those who engage in terrorism or other forms of paramilitary activity.</p>",,"Lord Dunlop",,"2016-10-31T10:50:04.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605486/answer","Biography information for Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605486/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605486/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-10-18","Belfast Agreement","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the concept of parity of esteem, as outlined in the Belfast Agreement 1998, applies to (1) members of the armed forces who served in Northern Ireland but reside in another part of the UK, (2) members of terrorist organisations who were active in Northern Ireland and reside there, and (3) members of terrorist organisations who were active in Northern Ireland but reside in the Republic of Ireland.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL2406"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605487","Department for Education","false","2016-10-27","<p>The Government believes that every child should experience a high quality creative education throughout their time at school. That is why subjects such as music, art and design, drama and dance are included in the National Curriculum for 5-14 year olds. The National Curriculum is compulsory for maintained schools. Academies and free schools are not required to teach the National Curriculum but can use it as a benchmark. They can also use their freedoms to innovate and build more stretching and tailored curricula, to meet the particular needs of their pupils or their local area or the particular ethos of the school.</p><p> </p><p>All schools, including academies and free schools, must provide a broad and balanced curriculum that promotes the spiritual, moral, cultural, mental and physical development of pupils at the school and of society.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-10-27T16:27:04.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605487/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605487/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605487/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-18","Arts: Curriculum","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will give further consideration to including the arts and other creative industries within future school curricula.","false","Biography information for The Earl of Glasgow",,"The Earl of Glasgow","HL2407"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605488","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-26","<p>The UK participated in the original US-led 'Train and Equip' programme for vetted Syrian opposition forces fighting Daesh in 2015. The Ministry of Defence announced on 25 October 2016, that up to 20 UK personnel will be deploying to locations in the region, but outside Syria, to contribute to the refined and restarted programme. Their role will be to train selected members of vetted moderate Syrian opposition groups in the skills they need to continue to take the fight to Daesh. The UK is not participating in the &quot;Equip&quot; element of this programme.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe","HL2409","2016-10-26T11:19:51.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605488/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605488/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605488/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-18","Syria: Military Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have supplied any anti-aircraft weapons to rebel forces fighting in Syria.","false","Biography information for Lord Empey",,"Lord Empey","HL2408"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605489","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-26","<p>The UK participated in the original US-led 'Train and Equip' programme for vetted Syrian opposition forces fighting Daesh in 2015. The Ministry of Defence announced on 25 October 2016, that up to 20 UK personnel will be deploying to locations in the region, but outside Syria, to contribute to the refined and restarted programme. Their role will be to train selected members of vetted moderate Syrian opposition groups in the skills they need to continue to take the fight to Daesh. The UK is not participating in the &quot;Equip&quot; element of this programme.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe","HL2408","2016-10-26T11:19:51.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605489/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605489/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605489/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-18","Syria: Military Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they are providing any military training to rebel forces fighting in Syria.","false","Biography information for Lord Empey",,"Lord Empey","HL2409"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605490","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-31","<p>The UK Government recognises states and not governments. We take the position that the Asad regime has lost legitimacy through having murdered, tortured, gassed and bombed the Syrian people.</p><p>The UK Government supports the Syrian moderate opposition including the National Coalition of Syrian Opposition and Revolutionary Forces and the High Negotiations Committee, the umbrella body representing the opposition in negotiations on Syria's future, of which the National Coalition is a part. The High Negotiations Committee brings together the broadest based opposition in Syria, striving to represent all Syrians who want to build a democratic and pluralistic future for the country.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-10-31T14:39:49.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605490/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605490/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605490/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-18","Syria: Politics and Government","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government who they recognise as the legitimate government of Syria.","false","Biography information for Lord Empey",,"Lord Empey","HL2410"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605491","Department for International Trade","false","2016-11-02","<p>The Government has been clear in its support for the EU-Canada Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement (CETA). This approach is in line with our commitment to back the EU’s trade agenda and participate constructively in decision-making on trade while the UK remains a member of the EU.</p>",,"Lord Price",,"2016-11-02T11:55:07.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605491/answer","Biography information for Lord Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605491/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605491/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-18","Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they support the proposed trade deal between the EU and Canada.","false","Biography information for Lord Empey",,"Lord Empey","HL2411"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605492","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-27","<p>Until we complete our withdrawal negotiations, the UK remains a full member of the EU, with all the rights and responsibilities of membership. The UK Government has been clear in its support for the EU-Canada Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement (CETA). This approach is in line with our commitment to back the EU’s trade agenda and participate constructively in decision-making on trade while the UK remains a member of the EU.</p><p>The negotiations between the European Commission and Canada on CETA were concluded in August 2014. A legal revision of the text making further amendments was completed in February 2016.</p>",,"Lord Price",,"2016-10-27T15:19:10.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605492/answer","Biography information for Lord Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605492/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605492/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-18","Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether, in the light of the UK's decision to leave the EU, the proposed trade deal between the EU and Canada should be amended to take account of the consequent reduction in the population of the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Empey",,"Lord Empey","HL2412"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605493","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-01","<p>All public debt issued by the UK government is denominated in pounds sterling. Therefore, any changes in the value of the currency do not affect the UK government’s indebtedness.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2016-11-01T13:14:46.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605493/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605493/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605493/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-18","Sterling","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the impact of the fall in the value of sterling on the UK’s indebtedness.","false","Biography information for Lord Empey",,"Lord Empey","HL2413"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605494","Department of Health","false","2016-10-31","<p>In developing <em>Childhood Obesity: A Plan for Action</em> we have been clear that we considered a number of different policies and have focused on the ones that are likely to have the biggest impact on childhood obesity.</p><p> </p><p>The policies in the plan are informed by the latest research and evidence, including from the Scientific Advisory Committee on Nutrition report <em>Carbohydrates and Health</em>, Public Health England’s evidence package <em>Sugar reduction: the evidence for action</em>, other Government departments, debates in the House of Commons and various reports from key stakeholders including the House of Commons Health Select Committee.</p><p> </p><p>Current restrictions on the advertising of less healthy food and drink in the United Kingdom are amongst the toughest in the world. Alongside this, we welcome the action taken by forward thinking retailers on promotions. These voluntary actions mean that business can move more quickly and go beyond what regulation would permit.</p><p> </p><p>We are confident that the measures we have announced will make a real difference and estimate that childhood obesity rates could be reduced by around a fifth (330,000) over the next ten years. Though we are clear in our goals and firm in the action we will take, this plan represents the start of a conversation, rather than the final word.</p><p> </p><p>Copies of<em> Carbohydrates and</em> <em>Health</em> and<em> Sugar reduction: the evidence for action </em>are attached.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL2415","2016-10-31T13:41:04.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605494/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605494/answer","SACN Carbohydrates and Health.pdf ; PHE Sugar reduction The evidence for action.pdf","SACN Carbohydrates and Health.pdf ; PHE Sugar reduction The evidence for action.pdf","SACN Carbohydrates & Health ; PHE Sugar Reduction","SACN Carbohydrates & Health ; PHE Sugar Reduction","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605494/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-18","Obesity: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what consideration they gave to proposals to regulate retail price promotions on unhealthy foods as part of their <i>Childhood Obesity: A Plan for Action</i> and, if they were not considered appropriate, why not.","false","Biography information for Lord Balfe",,"Lord Balfe","HL2414"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605495","Department of Health","false","2016-10-31","<p>In developing <em>Childhood Obesity: A Plan for Action</em> we have been clear that we considered a number of different policies and have focused on the ones that are likely to have the biggest impact on childhood obesity.</p><p> </p><p>The policies in the plan are informed by the latest research and evidence, including from the Scientific Advisory Committee on Nutrition report <em>Carbohydrates and Health</em>, Public Health England’s evidence package <em>Sugar reduction: the evidence for action</em>, other Government departments, debates in the House of Commons and various reports from key stakeholders including the House of Commons Health Select Committee.</p><p> </p><p>Current restrictions on the advertising of less healthy food and drink in the United Kingdom are amongst the toughest in the world. Alongside this, we welcome the action taken by forward thinking retailers on promotions. These voluntary actions mean that business can move more quickly and go beyond what regulation would permit.</p><p> </p><p>We are confident that the measures we have announced will make a real difference and estimate that childhood obesity rates could be reduced by around a fifth (330,000) over the next ten years. Though we are clear in our goals and firm in the action we will take, this plan represents the start of a conversation, rather than the final word.</p><p> </p><p>Copies of<em> Carbohydrates and</em> <em>Health</em> and<em> Sugar reduction: the evidence for action </em>are attached.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL2414","2016-10-31T13:41:04.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605495/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605495/answer","SACN Carbohydrates and Health.pdf ; PHE Sugar reduction The evidence for action.pdf","SACN Carbohydrates and Health.pdf ; PHE Sugar reduction The evidence for action.pdf","SACN Carbohydrates & Health ; PHE Sugar Reduction","SACN Carbohydrates & Health ; PHE Sugar Reduction","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605495/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-18","Obesity: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what consideration they gave to proposals to ban the advertising of unhealthy foods aimed specifically at children, and before the nine o'clock watershed, as part of their <i>Childhood Obesity: A Plan for Action</i> and, if such proposals were not considered appropriate, why not.","false","Biography information for Lord Balfe",,"Lord Balfe","HL2415"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605496","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-11-01","<p>UK companies are active in a range of sectors in Turkey, and the UK is consistently among the country’s top sources of foreign investment. The failed coup in Turkey on 15 July and its aftermath has had some short term impact, and the political situation remains challenging. The Turkish economy is well under-pinned and offers significant opportunities for investors in the medium and long term, particularly if the government proceeds with planned structural reforms.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-11-01T15:08:11.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605496/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605496/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605496/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-18","Turkey: Overseas Investment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their assessment of the political situation facing UK companies contemplating investing in Turkey.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL2416"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605497","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-10-25","<p>Charity trustees, almost all of whom are unpaid, set levels of executive remuneration and must do so acting in the best interests of the charity. A 2014 study by The National Council for Voluntary Organisations found that senior executives in charities were generally paid substantially less than for similar roles in the public or private sectors. Charities are legally required to provide details of the number of staff in pay bands over £60,000 in their publicly available annual reports, and many charities go further in their accountability and publish full details as a matter of good practice.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde",,"2016-10-25T16:02:32.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605497/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605497/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605497/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-18","Charities: Pay","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their assessment of the current levels of, and recent increases in, the total remuneration paid to the executive heads of the major charities in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL2417"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605498","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-01","<p>The Government is very clear that good design is a key aspect of sustainable development, is indivisible from good planning, and should contribute positively to making places better for people. It wants to see new developments that function well and add to the overall quality of the area, that establish a strong sense of place by using streetscapes and buildings to create attractive and comfortable places to live, work and visit.</p><p>The National Planning Policy Framework makes clear that planning policies and decisions should take account of the different roles and character of different areas and recognise the intrinsic character and beauty of the countryside.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-11-01T15:43:06.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605498/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605498/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605498/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-18","Housing: Construction","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their assessment of the importance of landscape quality when new housing is built on greenfield sites.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL2418"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605499","Department for Education","false","2016-11-07","<p>The Government is clear that all schools should make provision for high-quality sex and relationship education, which is a vital part of preparing young people for life in modern Britain.</p><p> </p><p>Academies, like maintained schools, must teach a broad and balanced curriculum and in respect of sex and relationship education, they must - under the terms of their funding agreement - have regard to the Secretary of State’s statutory Sex and Relationship Education guidance published in 2000.</p><p> </p><p>The issue of statutory personal, social, health and economic education and sex and relationship education was raised during the Education Select Committee session in September. The Secretary of State agreed that we need to look again at how schools deliver high-quality personal, social, health and economic education including sex and relationship education. The Government is considering all the options and will come to a view in due course.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash","HL2420","2016-11-07T14:27:18.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605499/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605499/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605499/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-18","Sex and Relationship Education","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the proposal to change the status of all secondary schools in England to become academies would mean that those schools which are now maintained schools will no longer have an obligation to deliver sex and relationship education.","false","Biography information for Lord Northbourne",,"Lord Northbourne","HL2419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605500","Department for Education","false","2016-11-07","<p>The Government is clear that all schools should make provision for high-quality sex and relationship education, which is a vital part of preparing young people for life in modern Britain.</p><p> </p><p>Academies, like maintained schools, must teach a broad and balanced curriculum and in respect of sex and relationship education, they must - under the terms of their funding agreement - have regard to the Secretary of State’s statutory Sex and Relationship Education guidance published in 2000.</p><p> </p><p>The issue of statutory personal, social, health and economic education and sex and relationship education was raised during the Education Select Committee session in September. The Secretary of State agreed that we need to look again at how schools deliver high-quality personal, social, health and economic education including sex and relationship education. The Government is considering all the options and will come to a view in due course.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash","HL2419","2016-11-07T14:27:18.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605500/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605500/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605500/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-18","Sex and Relationship Education","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to introduce legislation to require all schools, including academies, to provide high quality sex and relationship education as part of their syllabus.","false","Biography information for Lord Northbourne",,"Lord Northbourne","HL2420"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605501","Department for Education","false","2016-11-07","<p>Schools collect a range of information on pupils for their own purposes. Full details of all the data collected by law is accessible via the links in the attached list.</p><p> </p><p>Some of this information is required to be submitted to the Department via various collections which are undertaken throughout the school year. The main types of information collected by the Department are:</p><ul><li>pupil identifiers (name, date of birth, etc)</li><li>pupil characteristics (gender, ethnicity, language, etc.)</li><li>pupil attendance and exclusions</li><li>pupil special educational needs</li><li>pupil attainment and teacher assessments</li></ul><p>The school census has collected such data at pupil level from the introduction of the Pupil Level Annual School Census in 2002.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-11-07T14:27:53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605501/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605501/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605501/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-18","Pupils: Personal Records","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what information schools are required by law to collect regarding their pupils.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL2421"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605502","Department for Education","false","2016-11-01","<p>It is for individual higher education providers to determine the minimum criteria for entry onto their courses.</p><p> </p><p>However, private providers must meet a number of conditions to gain designation for student support. These include having a successful Quality Assurance Agency Higher Education Review (Alternative Providers), which tests providers’ recruitment, selection and admission policies and procedures, as well as ensuring that all students recruited onto courses designated for student support meet a minimum English Language requirement.</p><p> </p><p>The Department monitors whether providers comply with the conditions of designation to ensure providers are held accountable and to protect the student and public interest. If at any point the Department determines that the conditions have not been met, it could put in place a range of sanctions, including the removal of course designation.</p>",,"Viscount Younger of Leckie",,"2016-11-01T15:25:16.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605502/answer","Biography information for Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605502/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605502/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-18","Higher Education: Admissions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what oversight is provided to private higher education providers enrolling students onto degree courses to ensure minimum criteria are met for entry onto undergraduate degrees.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL2422"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605503","Department for Education","false","2016-11-01","<p>The UK Quality Code, which the Quality Assurance Agency’s Higher Education Review (Alternative Providers) uses to assess private providers, sets out the following expectations about recruitment, selection and admission to higher education:</p><p>“Recruitment, selection, and admission policies and procedures adhere to the principles of fair admission. They are transparent, reliable, valid, inclusive and underpinned by appropriate organisational structures and processes. They support higher education providers in the selection of students who are able to complete their programme.”</p><p> </p><p>It is a condition of designation for student support that private providers maintain successful outcomes from these QAA reviews and annual monitoring. QAA's Concerns Scheme investigates specific concerns about the management of academic quality and standards, including recruitment, selection and admissions.</p>",,"Viscount Younger of Leckie",,"2016-11-01T15:26:36.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605503/answer","Biography information for Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605503/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605503/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-18","Higher Education: Admissions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what regulatory provision the Quality Assurance Agency for Higher Education makes to ensure that private higher education providers maintain minimum admission standards for undergraduate degrees and provide value for money.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL2423"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605504","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-10-26","<p>A letter was sent to the Noble Lord and deposited in the House of Lords Library on Thursday 21st October.</p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde",,"2016-10-26T11:19:21.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605504/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605504/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605504/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-18","BBC: Royal Charters","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the remarks by Lord Ashton of Hyde on 12 October (HL Deb, col 1996), whether they will clarify when the noble Lords can expect to receive written responses to the points they raised during the debate.","false","Biography information for Lord Lester of Herne Hill",,"Lord Lester of Herne Hill","HL2424"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605505","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-24","<p>The Competition and Markets Authority (CMA) was formed in 2014 after the Office of Fair Trading and the Competition Commission were merged. It has the function to carry out investigations into sectors where there is risk of anti-competitive behaviour.</p><p>Since its inception in 2014, the CMA has carried out five Phase 1 merger investigations into the bus industry. The estimated cost for these investigations was £308,229.55. The Government does not hold information on the cost of individual investigations undertaken by the Office of Fair Trading or the Competition Commission.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-10-24T16:45:42.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605505/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605505/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605505/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-18","Bus Services: Competition","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much has been spent by the Competition and Markets Authority conducting investigations into the bus industry, including fees paid to consultants and legal fees, over the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradshaw",,"Lord Bradshaw","HL2425"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605506","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-24","<p>In the last ten years there were 43 investigations involving bus companies, 15 for rail, 11 for airports, 2 for trams, 1 for cars and 1 other.</p><p>These figures include investigations carried out by the Competition and Markets Authority’s predecessors (the Office of Fair Trading and the Competition Commission).</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-10-24T16:45:59.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605506/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605506/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605506/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-18","Bus Services: Competition","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many investigations have been conducted by the Competition and Markets Authority into the bus industry over the last 10 years and how the total number compares to other sectors in the transport industry.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradshaw",,"Lord Bradshaw","HL2426"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605507","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-28","<p>Emissions standards for new buses and coaches are not set by any of the parties named, but by the government through EU type approval legislation. Type Approval Authorities such as the UK’s Vehicle Certification Agency (VCA) are responsible for ensuring that these standards are met. In-service emissions checking is carried out at the statutory annual inspection by the Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency (DVSA).</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-10-28T13:16:27.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605507/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605507/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605507/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-18","Buses: Exhaust Emissions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government to what extent emission standards for buses and coaches are set by (1) the Traffic Commissioners, (2) the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency and (3) highway authorities; and who is responsible for ensuring that these standards are adhered to.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradshaw",,"Lord Bradshaw","HL2427"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605508","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-01","Highway authorities have a wide range of powers that they can use to deal with particular traffic management issues. A number of enforcement authorities are involved as well and, depending on the issue, includes local authorities themselves, Transport for London, Highways England and the Police. The Government does not keep central records of which enforcement authorities operate which regimes and to collate that information would not be possible except at disproportionate cost.",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-11-01T15:05:50.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605508/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605508/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605508/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-18","Road Traffic Control","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what powers are available to highway authorities to enforce traffic management law; how many highway authorities have decided to use any powers available to them, and which highway authorities have chosen not to do so.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradshaw",,"Lord Bradshaw","HL2428"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605509","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-25","<p>The independent Office for Budget Responsibility (OBR) is responsible for producing forecasts for the UK economy and public finances. It publishes regular Forecast Evaluation Reports (FERs) in which it compares its forecasts to subsequent outturns and explains any forecast errors.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2016-10-25T16:17:53.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605509/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605509/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605509/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-18","Economic Situation: Forecasts","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they (1) have confidence in the economic forecasting capability of HM Treasury, (2) have evaluated the performance of HM Treasury forecasters, and (3) have considered the case for outsourcing some or all of HM Treasury's forecasting functions to another organisation.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL2429"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605510","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-01","<p>The Department for International Development's (DFID) Inclusive Societies department leads the Department's work on ageing. The Minister of State, Rory Stewart, has responsibility for Inclusive Societies department’s work.</p><p>Many DFID programmes reach and include older people, for example on health systems strengthening and eye care, or specific programmes for the poorest including supporting slum dwellers in Tanzania or supporting widows resulting from the Genocide in Rwanda.</p><p>Ageing also features in DFID country level poverty analyses as a key factor in understanding poverty. In addition to this DFID is taking a global leadership role to push for better quality and use of age disaggregated data to ensure that the Sustainable Development Goals leave no one behind. DFID hosted a series of high profile events on this subject in May and is working towards the publication of an action plan detailing next steps early in 2017.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2016-11-01T15:34:54.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605510/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605510/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605510/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-18","Developing Countries: Older People","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government to what extent ageing and older people in developing countries remain an issue of concern for the Department for International Development, why this matter no longer forms part of the Department's ministerial portfolios, and whether ageing still forms part of the Department’s Inclusive Societies work.","false","Biography information for Baroness Northover",,"Baroness Northover","HL2430"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605971","Home Office","false","2016-10-25","<p>In June 2016 the Government published a memorandum to the House of Lords Select Committee on the post-legislative scrutiny of the Licensing Act 2003.</p><p>The memorandum provides an assessment of how the Licensing Act 2003 has operated since its commencement in 2005 and was prepared by the Home Office with contribution from the Department for Culture Media and Sport, Department of Health and Public Health England.</p><p>The memorandum is available at: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/post-legislative-scrutiny-of-the-licensing-act-2003</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-10-25T12:53:03.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605971/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605971/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605971/answer","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/605971/answer/previousversion/16038","Biography information for Sarah Newton","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-18","Local Government: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the adequacy of licensing powers available to local authorities.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","906731"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606024","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-24","<p>The provision and location of Post Offices is the operational responsibility of Post Office Limited.</p><p> </p><p>Any proposal by Post Office Limited to relocate a post office within a community includes a six week local consultation conducted by the Post Office to let the community know what is happening and seek feedback from interested customers and stakeholders within the community. The Post Office carefully considers all feedback received during the consultation process before making a final decision on whether to relocate.</p><p> </p><p>The Government recognises the importance of post offices to communities and will have invested £2 billion in the Post Office during the period 2010 to 2018 to maintain the network and invest in transformation of the business which includes money to help relocate post offices to more sustainable locations in their communities. This investment has led to the highest level of network stability in decades.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-10-24T09:44:20.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606024/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606024/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606024/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-18","Post Offices: Location","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what support his Department provides for communities in which Post Offices require relocation.","false","Biography information for Tom Pursglove","Corby","Tom Pursglove","906734"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619062","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-10-24","<p>One person without a home is one too many. That is why we launched a new £40 million Homelessness Prevention programme to tackle homelessness and rough sleeping.</p><p>This will enable authorities to support vulnerable people, preventing them from becoming homeless, and ensuring those who do have somewhere safe to stay.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","906744","2016-10-24T16:09:19.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619062/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619062/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619062/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-18","Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what recent steps his Department has taken to help rough sleepers and homeless people.","false","Biography information for John Glen","Salisbury","John Glen","906746"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619063","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-10-24","<p>One person without a home is one too many. That is why we launched a new £40 million Homelessness Prevention programme to tackle homelessness and rough sleeping.</p><p>This will enable authorities to support vulnerable people, preventing them from becoming homeless, and ensuring those who do have somewhere safe to stay.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","906746","2016-10-24T16:09:19.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619063/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619063/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/619063/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-18","Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what recent steps his Department has taken to help rough sleepers and homeless people.","false","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer","906744"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/621209","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-10-26","<p>Significant progress has been made, including on welfare reform, and towards the establishment of the Independent Reporting Commission on paramilitary activity. We are working closely with the Executive and Irish Government on outstanding commitments. The devolution of corporation tax powers and building consensus for the legacy bodies are top priorities.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-10-26T14:22:15.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/621209/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/621209/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/621209/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-10-18","Stormont House Agreement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what recent progress has been made on the implementation of the Stormont House and Fresh Start Agreements.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","Wycombe","Steve Baker","906768"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/621210","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-10-26","<p>Leaders in both Ireland and the UK have been unequivocal – both want to maintain the current arrangement and avoid the introduction of physical border controls within the Common Travel Area.</p><p>I attend regular meetings with representatives of the Irish Government and we are working together to achieve this outcome.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-10-26T14:24:15.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/621210/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/621210/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/621210/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-10-18","Borders: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what progress is being made on maintaining an open border between the UK and the Republic of Ireland after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","906771"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603936","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-31","<p>This information requested is not collated centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2016-10-31T12:25:04.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603936/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603936/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603936/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-17","State Retirement Pensions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answers by Lord Freud on 15 September (HL1460, HL1461 and HL1462), what assessment they have made of (1) the proportion of addresses held by the Department for Work and Pensions that are incorrect, and (2) the number of people who will not have received a letter informing them of the change in their state pension age.","false","Biography information for Baroness Altmann",,"Baroness Altmann","HL2332"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603937","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-31","<p>The Department has a robust process in place to review all incorrect address returns and properly scrutinise and update customer account details when an address is confirmed. Letters are issued to the latest address held on our records. DWP takes all reasonable steps to determine the correct address. For State Pensions this may include contact through Local Authority or a DWP Visiting Officer. Where an updated address is confirmed the customer account details are amended.</p><p>Information on the number of individuals who had letters returned due to incorrect address details, and details on resending letters is not collated centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2016-10-31T12:25:30.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603937/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603937/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603937/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-17","State Retirement Pensions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Freud on 15 September (HL1462), what action was taken to trace new addresses and re-send letters to those affected by the increase in State Pension Age under the Pensions Act 2011; and for whom letters sent between January 2012 and November 2013 were returned due to the Department for Work and Pensions having the incorrect address.","false","Biography information for Baroness Altmann",,"Baroness Altmann","HL2333"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603938","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-10-31","<p>Letters are issued to the latest address held on our records. Whilst the onus is on our citizens to notify appropriate Departments of their current address, DWP takes all reasonable steps to determine the correct address when letters are returned. This includes scrutinising all available DWP systems to determine if a revised address is held. At the time of the age equalisation communications campaign the process for State Pension included contact through Local Authorities or a DWP Visiting Officer. Where an updated address is confirmed the customer account details are amended.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2016-10-31T14:03:34.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603938/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603938/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603938/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-10-17","State Retirement Pensions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Freud on 15 September (HL1462), what happens to letters that are returned undelivered when incorrect details are held.","false","Biography information for Baroness Altmann",,"Baroness Altmann","HL2334"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603939","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-26","<p>Both the UK Special Representative to Sudan and South Sudan and Her Majesty’s Ambassador to Sudan engage with opposition groups regularly, most recently at a joint meeting with the Sudan Call alliance of opposition groups in Khartoum in September. The UK Special Representative also met with representatives of the National Umma Party, including Sadiq El Mahdi, in Addis Ababa on 23 September. We will continue to develop our relations with these groups both in Sudan and elsewhere.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-10-26T14:52:52.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603939/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603939/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603939/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-17","Sudan: Politics and Government","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when the Foreign and Commonwealth Office Sudan Unit and the British Ambassador to the Republic of Sudan last engaged with opposition groups in Sudan, in particular those members of the Sudan Call alliance; and, following the signing of the Sudan Roadmap Agreement, whether a delegation from the Sudan Call alliance will be invited to London in order to deepen political engagement with that group.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL2335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603940","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-26","<p>​We are not aware of any reports that Sudanese-manufactured ammunition has been used by Boko Haram. We fully support the EU arms embargo on Sudan as well as the UN arms embargo on Darfur.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-10-26T14:53:09.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603940/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603940/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603940/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-17","Nigeria: Boko Haram","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of reports that ammunition used by Boko Haram in Nigeria is manufactured in Sudan.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL2336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603941","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-26","<p>The Khartoum Process does not have a defined single fund, but draws from several different sources of EU funding; including the Better Migration Management Fund and the EU Emergency Trust Fund for Africa.</p><p>The UK, as the current Chair of the Khartoum Process, works closely with the Secretariat to maintain a map of current and proposed projects, and ensure effective coordination and monitoring. The European Commission has responsibility for assessing implementation against the Valetta benchmarks and outcomes, and conducting the full audit and review of the EU funding programmes.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-10-26T14:53:39.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603941/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603941/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603941/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-17","Horn of Africa: EU Immigration","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how they intend to evaluate the use of  €46 million earmarked for the Khartoum Process; what benchmarks and agreed criteria have been developed to guide the Process; and what procedures have been put in place to monitor, audit, and review the efficacy of the Process.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL2337"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603942","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-26","<p>​All EU funds committed to the Khartoum Process are managed by Member States' Development Agencies or International Organisations. No funding will be channelled through the beneficiary countries' government structures.</p><p>We are deeply concerned by the reports of collusion between Sudanese security officials and human traffickers, and have raised this issue directly with the government of Sudan as part of our wider engagement on migration. The UK is supporting the Sudanese judiciary to implement new anti-trafficking legislation by helping them improve their understanding of both this and the UN Trafficking in Persons Protocol.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-10-26T15:00:03.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603942/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603942/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603942/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-17","Horn of Africa: EU Immigration","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what procedures have been put in place to ensure that EU funds committed to the Khartoum Process are not embezzled by corrupt officials; and whether they have investigated whether there has been collusion between Sudanese security officials and human traffickers.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL2338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603943","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-26","<p>We are concerned by the reported use of the Rapid Support Forces (RSF) to tackle migration in Sudan and have raised these concerns with the government of Sudan, most recently during the visit of the UK Special Representative to Sudan and South Sudan in September. We have also made clear that our cooperation on migration will necessarily be guided by our human rights principles. The EU has also raised the role of the RSF with the government of Sudan and has made absolutely clear that no funding aligned with the Khartoum Process will be provided to them.</p><p>The government of Sudan has undertaken some of its disarmament commitments under the Doha Document for Peace in Darfur (DDPD), but together with our international partners we continue to urge them to do more. The UK is a member of the DDPD's Implementation Follow-Up Commission (IFC), which we use to press for progress on disarmament and other areas of the DDPD's implementation. The most recent meeting of the IFC was in May 2016.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-10-26T15:01:43.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603943/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603943/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603943/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-17","Sudan","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what role armed militias play in enforcing Sudan’s commitments under the Khartoum Process; whether they are being used to enforce border controls and to capture migrants; and what action the regime took, under its commitments in the Doha Document for Peace, 2012, to disarm militias.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL2339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603944","Department of Health","false","2016-10-31","<p>The Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority has advised that no such approach has been made to the Authority.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-10-31T13:28:02.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603944/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603944/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603944/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-17","In Vitro Fertilisation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether any approach has been made to the Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority regarding the possibility of performing spindle-chromosome complex transfer in the UK; and if so, when any such approaches were made and by whom.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL2340"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603945","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-24","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy has introduced robust Employment Tribunal enforcement processes, which can ultimately lead to a referral to a debt collection agency. A new process implemented in April 2016 allows for a penalty to be issued. The penalty is calculated as 50% of the value of the tribunal award up to a maximum of £5,000.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-10-24T12:24:46.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603945/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603945/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603945/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-17","Employment Tribunals Service","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the research commissioned by the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills in 2013 <i>Payment of Tribunal Awards</i> showing that one-third of employment tribunal awards remained unpaid and only 49 per cent of successful applicants received their full awarded compensation, what steps they are taking to ensure that employment tribunal awards are paid in full.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL2341"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603946","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-10-31","<p>We are committed to giving magistrates the strongest possible role in a more proportionate courts system, now and in the future.</p><p> </p><p>Magistrates and District Judges bring different but valuable skills to our justice system. We are working with magistrates to review their role to make sure that the justice system is making full use of their skills, and that they are dealing with more of the crimes that affect and matter most to their communities.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2016-10-31T17:53:50.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603946/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603946/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603946/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-10-17","Magistrates","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of increasing reliance on district judges, what role they envisage for lay magistrates.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL2342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603947","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-10-25","<p>The East West Cycle Superhighway is a Transport for London (TfL) project carried out by their contractors. The Royal Parks has issued licenses to TfL to permit the work to take place within the parks. Part of the cycle route in Hyde Park is already open. TfL estimates that the remainder of the Hyde Park route will be open in the New Year.</p><p> </p><p>The work in St James’s and Green Parks is being planned in stages and the complete route should be finished by next summer although parts may be open sooner.</p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde",,"2016-10-25T16:01:29.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603947/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603947/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603947/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-17","Royal Parks: Cycleways","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why the Royal Parks have not yet completed the construction of the sections of the East-West London Super Cycle highway which are planned to pass through Hyde Park and St James Park; and when it is expected that the work will be complete and open to cyclists.","false","Biography information for Lord Berkeley",,"Lord Berkeley","HL2343"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603948","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-24","<p>UK aviation security experts have worked closely with their Egyptian counterparts on the ground, sharing their expertise in establishing effective security arrangements. We continue to work in partnership in a spirit of cooperation, and are grateful for Egypt's close engagement and partnership. We look forward to achieving the return of flights once we can be assured that the necessary security environment can be sustained.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-10-24T12:15:09.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603948/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603948/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603948/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-17","Aviation: Egypt","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the impact on the British tourism and airline industries of the ban on air flights between the UK and Sharm el Sheikh.","false","Biography information for Lord Dear",,"Lord Dear","HL2344"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603949","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-10-26","<p>There are 13 members of Ofcom’s Content Board which advises the Ofcom Board and Executive on content matters, covering television, radio and video-on-demand quality and standards. The Board’s members have experience from across the broadcasting industry including Sky, BBC, ITV, Channel 4 and S4C. 9 of the current 13 members have previously been employed by or have worked for the BBC. The amount of experience and the seniority of these roles varies considerably within that.</p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde",,"2016-10-26T13:01:57.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603949/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603949/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603949/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-17","Ofcom Content Board","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what proportion of the Ofcom Content Board are former employees of the BBC.","false","Biography information for Lord Forsyth of Drumlean",,"Lord Forsyth of Drumlean","HL2345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603950","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-27","<p>The department is permanently headquartered at 9 Downing Street. This will not change and Ministers will continue to operate from this building. Staff are also accommodated in 70 Whitehall.</p><p>We are working with the Government Property Unit as where to locate further staff on a more permanent basis.</p><p>DExEU staff will continue to be employed on the basis of being 'on loan' from a wide variety of departments and will not permanently transfer departments. No staff have been formally moved from DExEU to the Ministry of Defence, the Foreign and Commonwealth Office, the Cabinet Office, or other government departments.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley","HL2347","2016-10-27T10:59:14.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603950/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603950/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603950/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-17","Department for Exiting the European Union: Buildings","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the Department for Exiting the EU plans to remain within the Cabinet Office premises or to relocate; and if it plans to relocate, whether it will move to its own building, or move, in its entirety or in part, to premises of another government department.","false","Biography information for Baroness Goudie",,"Baroness Goudie","HL2346"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603951","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-27","<p>The department is permanently headquartered at 9 Downing Street. This will not change and Ministers will continue to operate from this building. Staff are also accommodated in 70 Whitehall.</p><p>We are working with the Government Property Unit as where to locate further staff on a more permanent basis.</p><p>DExEU staff will continue to be employed on the basis of being 'on loan' from a wide variety of departments and will not permanently transfer departments. No staff have been formally moved from DExEU to the Ministry of Defence, the Foreign and Commonwealth Office, the Cabinet Office, or other government departments.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley","HL2346","2016-10-27T10:59:14.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603951/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603951/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603951/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-17","Department for Exiting the European Union: Staff","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they are planning to transfer to other government departments any of the staff currently working within the Department for Exiting the EU, and if so, what is their estimate of the proportion of staff who will be moved to (1) the Ministry of Defence, (2) the Foreign and Commonwealth Office, (3) the Cabinet Office, or (4) other government departments.","false","Biography information for Baroness Goudie",,"Baroness Goudie","HL2347"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603952","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-27","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union now has over 250 staff and the expertise of 120 officials in Brussels, and is continuing to grow.</p><p>We are not in a position to give a total number of job applications as recruitment is ongoing and we will not be giving a running commentary. Our aim is to have a streamlined Department, while ensuring the right skills and experience to get the best outcome for the UK.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2016-10-27T10:57:46.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603952/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603952/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603952/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-17","Department for Exiting the European Union: Vacancies","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many roles within the Department for Exiting the EU are currently unfilled; and how many job applications have been received for those roles.","false","Biography information for Baroness Goudie",,"Baroness Goudie","HL2348"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603953","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-10-25","<p>We have had no discussions with the World Chess Federation on this matter. Visitors to any country should refer to FCO advice when travelling abroad, including abiding by local laws and customs.</p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde",,"2016-10-25T16:02:57.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603953/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603953/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603953/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-17","Chess: Iran","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the World Chess Federation's decision to enforce a requirement on all competitors in the Women's World Chess Championship 2017 in Iran to wear the hijab, and what discussions they have had with, and what advice they have given to, UK Chess Associations about the safety of UK citizens competing in the event.","false","Biography information for Lord Maginnis of Drumglass",,"Lord Maginnis of Drumglass","HL2349"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603954","Home Office","false","2016-10-27","<p>All applications for visas, entry clearances and leave to enter at the border are considered against the criteria set out in the published Immigration Rules (https://www.gov.uk/guidance/immigration-rules) regardless of the applicant’s nationality or where they live.</p><p>A variety of factors may be taken into account when considering the application, but that would depend upon the applicant’s personal circumstances and what they had applied to do in the UK.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-10-27T14:02:13.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603954/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603954/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603954/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-10-17","Visas: Israel","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what distinction they draw in issuing visas between Israeli citizens who live in Israel and those who live in illegal settlements in the West Bank.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL2350"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603955","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-31","<p>DFID is supporting the President’s Recovery Plan (PRP) that focuses on delivering its two health priorities to strengthen Sierra Leone’s health system post Ebola. They are:</p><p>(i) Prevent, detect and respond to epidemics to ensure zero cases of Ebola. DFID is providing £38.5million to support epidemic preparedness in the country by strengthening disease surveillance, laboratory services, maintaining a rapid deployable treatment centre and monitoring Ebola survivors. This programme has been operational since December 2015 and will finish in December 2017.</p><p>(ii) Saving the Lives of 600 women and 5,000 children. DFID is providing £150million over five years (2016 – 2021) to support the Government’s saving lives target by June 2017 and then increase the availability and quality of Reproductive Maternal Neonatal Child and Adolescent Health (RMNCAH) services by 2021. This is being done by equipping emergency obstetric centres, providing adolescent reproductive health services, increasing the availability of skilled health workers and by providing bed nets and free medicines to mothers and children. This programme commenced implementation this month.</p><p>Each health priority has a clearly defined work plan with milestones and is coordinated by the Ministry of Health. Progress against the milestones is monitored and reported weekly with the President reviewing progress each fortnight. District surveillance reports are submitted weekly to track the incidence of notifiable diseases (such as Ebola, Cholera and Lassa fever), detect clusters of unexplained deaths and trigger immediate investigation. In additional DFID is engaging in the longer term planning to strengthen Sierra Leone’s health system, including the development of a five year RMNCAH strategy.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2016-10-31T17:34:26.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603955/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603955/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603955/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-17","Sierra Leone: Health Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what progress has been made in setting up a coordinated and effective health care system in Sierra Leone, following the Ebola outbreak.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL2351"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603956","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-26","<p>​The UK regularly raises the issue of water in the Occupied Palestinian Territories with the Israeli authorities, including stressing the urgent need for Israel to take immediate and practical measures to ensure fair distribution of water in the West Bank and Gaza.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-10-26T15:02:07.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603956/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603956/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603956/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-17","Israel: Golan Heights","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they have had with the government of Israel concerning (1) the status of, and (2) the distribution of water resources from, the Golan Heights.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL2352"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603957","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-31","<p>The United Nations Relief and Works Agency for Palestine Refugees in the Near East (UNRWA) estimates that 110,000 Palestinian refugees have fled Syria since the onset of the conflict; 42,000 Palestinian refugees from Syria are estimated to be in Lebanon and 17,000 in Jordan, with the remainder in Egypt, Turkey and Europe.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2016-10-31T17:33:08.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603957/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603957/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603957/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-17","Syria: Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the number of refugees from Syria who are Palestinian in origin.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL2353"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603958","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-26","<p>While we have not had any discussions with the Israeli authorities on this specific issue, we continue to be clear with both sides that there must be a just, fair and agreed settlement for refugees as part of a negotiated two-state solution.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-10-26T15:02:29.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603958/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603958/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603958/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-17","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they have had with the government of Israel concerning the repatriation of Palestinian refugees fleeing Syria.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL2354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603959","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-28","<p>The Department for Transport plans to publish both Natural England’s review of the No Net Loss to Biodiversity metric and the Government’s response before the end of the HS2 Select Committee in the Lords.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-10-28T13:16:48.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603959/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603959/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603959/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-17","High Speed 2 Railway Line","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether Natural England are planning to report on net loss of biodiversity measurements in relation to Phase 1 of the HS2 project, as called for in the Report published in February of the House of Commons Select Committee on the High Speed Rail (London–West Midlands) Bill (HC129); and if so, when that report will be published.","false","Biography information for Baroness Young of Old Scone",,"Baroness Young of Old Scone","HL2355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603960","Department for Transport","false","2016-10-28","<p>The Government is considering carefully all the potential implications arising from the UK’s exit from the EU, including the implications of preserving the mutual recognition of disabled persons’ Blue Badges throughout the UK and EU. Until we leave, EU law still applies, so EU rules in this area will continue to apply in the UK, alongside national rules.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-10-28T13:57:07.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603960/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603960/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603960/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-10-17","Blue Badge Scheme","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will seek to preserve the mutual recognition of disabled persons’ Blue Badges throughout the UK and EU in their negotiations to leave the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Bowness",,"Lord Bowness","HL2356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603961","Department of Health","false","2016-10-25","<p>Nothing has yet been decided on whether the United Kingdom will seek to preserve the mutual recognition of the European Health Insurance Card after leaving the European Union. Officials in both the Department of Health and the Department for Exiting the European Union are considering the position and options available to us with the aim of achieving the best outcome for the UK health system and for the UK as a whole.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-10-25T16:33:06.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603961/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603961/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603961/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-17","Health Services: Reciprocal Arrangements","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will seek to preserve the mutual recognition of the European Health Insurance Card throughout the UK and EU in their negotiations to leave the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Bowness",,"Lord Bowness","HL2357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603962","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-24","<p>The Joint Unit on Euro-Atlantic Security Policy (EASP) was launched on 18 October 2016. Foreign and Commonwealth Office and Ministry of Defence colleagues are now co-located as a single team leading the Government's work on NATO policy, the EU's Common Security and Defence Policy, and Conventional Arms Control in Europe.</p><p>As set out in the 2015 Strategic Defence and Security Review, the UK remains fully and strongly committed to European defence and security. The EASP Joint Unit will continue to lead on these issues after the UK leaves the EU.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-10-24T14:21:46.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603962/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603962/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603962/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-17","Euro-Atlantic Security Policy Unit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the joint Euro-Atlantic Security Policy Unit, which was referred to in the National Security Strategy and Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015, has been formed; and what its future role is anticipated to be when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Bowness",,"Lord Bowness","HL2358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603963","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-27","<p>The Government will discuss with the EU and member states how best to continue cooperation.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2016-10-27T10:58:08.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603963/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603963/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603963/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-17","Disaster Relief","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the UK will continue to play an active role in the EU Civil Protection mechanism after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Bowness",,"Lord Bowness","HL2359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603964","Department of Health","false","2016-10-25","<p>Sustainability and Transformation Plans are local plans and have been developed locally. Neither the Department nor NHS England collects data on whether these plans have been developed with outside advice.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-10-25T16:29:41.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603964/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603964/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603964/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-17","NHS: Reorganisation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much money has been (1) spent, and (2) committed to be spent, on consultancies in the preparation of NHS sustainability and transformation plans.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL2360"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603965","Department of Health","false","2016-10-25","<p>Sustainability and Transformation Plans (STPs) themselves are drawn up collaboratively by existing organisations in the local areas, utilising existing resources. In addition, national bodies are working directly with STP teams to ensure local plans are as strong and deliverable as possible, and that financial plans achieve the best results for patients and communities within the resources available.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-10-25T16:30:22.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603965/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603965/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603965/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-17","NHS: Reorganisation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what governance arrangements are in place to ensure that expenditure committed in the preparation of NHS sustainability and transformation plans provides value for money.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL2361"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603966","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-24","<p>The Government strongly supported the more transparent and structured process that led to the recent appointment of the next UN Secretary-General and has promoted similar reforms in other multilateral organisations aimed at ensuring the best candidates apply for leadership roles. The scope for reform depends on the dynamics of each organisation, including their internal decision-making procedures and the views of other member states.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-10-24T14:22:23.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603966/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603966/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603966/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-17","International Organisations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the changes to the selection process for the UN Secretary General, whether they are planning to initiate a review of the selection processes for the President of the World Bank and for similar offices in other international financial institutions and UN specialised agencies.","false","Biography information for Lord Judd",,"Lord Judd","HL2362"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603967","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-24","The Government is aware of the ongoing border controversy between Guyana and Venezuela. This is a bilateral issue to be resolved between the two countries. We believe the 1899 Arbitral Award, to which we were a party, definitively settled the border. Both countries are signatories of the Geneva Agreement of 1966 which provides a range of mechanisms for dealing with this issue.",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-10-24T14:29:08.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603967/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603967/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603967/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-17","Venezuela: Guyana","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what recent assessment they have made of the government of Venezuela's claim to approximately two-thirds of the territory of Guyana, a Commonwealth member state.","false","Biography information for Lord Howell of Guildford",,"Lord Howell of Guildford","HL2363"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603968","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-31","<p>The UK is deeply concerned about the rising humanitarian needs of the Syrians trapped between the Syrian and Jordanian borders. UK government officials have been working hard to find a solution that allows the resumption of humanitarian aid while meeting the security concerns of the Government of Jordan. UK officials have been working closely with international partners, including the United States, the European Union and other international donors. Our international partners’ response and assessment of the situation on the berm is consistent with the UK government’s stance.</p><p>An agreement in principle has been reached with the Government of Jordan for the resumption of aid supplies to the border area within the coming weeks. This remains at the detailed planning stage but should ultimately provide more substantial aid, primarily food, water and daily essential items, and restore a basic medical provision for those present in the border area.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2016-10-31T16:55:20.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603968/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603968/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603968/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-17","Syria: Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to other members of the international community, and with what responses, concerning the large group of Syrians now trapped at the border with Jordan; and what plans they have for securing food and essential services for that group.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL2364"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603969","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-10-26","<p>Our first priority is to ensure British Nationals abroad are safe. As with all countries, the Foreign and Commonwealth Office travel advice for Tunisia is under constant review. We are working with Tunisian authorities to help improve their ability to mitigate against the threats to British nationals, including through protective security, airport security and incident response. We will change travel advice as soon as the threat level and security situation permit.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-10-26T15:03:14.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603969/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603969/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603969/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-10-17","Tunisia: Travel Information","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will review current travel advice for Tunisia, in the light of the improving situation there.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL2365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603970","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-31","<p>A comprehensive Review of the Monetary Policy Framework was published in 2013. The current remit for the Monetary Policy Committee reflects the assessment set out in the 2013 Review, which includes retaining a flexible inflation targeting framework, with a 2 per cent symmetric inflation target. The remit also states that the MPC may allow inflation to deviate from this target temporarily in order not to cause undesirable volatility in output due to the short-term trade-offs involved.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2016-10-31T15:30:20.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603970/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603970/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603970/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-17","Inflation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will explain the basis on which the inflation target for the Bank of England’s Monetary Policy Committee is set; and the circumstances in which that figure would be raised above two per cent.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL2366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603971","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-25","<p>The Government is in close contact with Nissan, as it is with the sector more broadly. It will be a priority of Government negotiations to support all UK based car manufacturers and ensure that their ability to export to and from the EU is not adversely affected by the UK's future relationship with the EU. However, we do not provide a running commentary on our discussions with individual companies.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-10-25T15:14:58.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603971/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603971/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603971/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-17","Motor Vehicles: UK Trade with EU","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will disclose the proposals made by the Prime Minister to Renault Nissan concerning protecting new investment in Sunderland from the impact of potential EU tariffs; and whether similar protection will be offered to other motor vehicle manufacturers, component suppliers and firms that compete with Renault Nissan for capital, labour and land.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL2367"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603972","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-26","<p>The Royal Navy has a long-term strategy for its expenditure which is managed through the Annual Budget Cycle, a process that focuses on delivering a balanced, affordable Defence Plan over a ten year time period. This is aligned with Defence policy and the direction provided by Strategic Defence and Security Reviews, which occur every five years.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-10-26T15:07:23.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603972/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603972/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603972/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-17","Navy: Expenditure","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by Earl Howe on 13 September (HL Deb, col 1390), what the long-term strategy of the Royal Navy's expenditure plans is.","false","Biography information for Lord Touhig",,"Lord Touhig","HL2368"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603973","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-26","<p>Should on-board engineers be unable to resolve a problem with any ship or submarine, there is a range of ways in which operational maintenance and repair can be delivered. This can include the deployment of a Royal Navy repair and maintenance party, or utilising well-established commercial arrangements and international agreements, such as the use of other countries' bases and facilities. This is particularly the case where resources and facilities are not available within the Ministry of Defence or are more effectively provided by a third party.</p>",,"Earl Howe","HL2372","2016-10-26T15:08:00.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603973/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603973/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603973/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-17","RFA Diligence","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what contingency plans have been put in place in the event of a mechanical failure of one of the Trafalgar Class submarines due to the withdrawal of the only Royal Navy repair ship RFA Diligence.","false","Biography information for Lord Touhig",,"Lord Touhig","HL2369"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603974","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-25","<p>We do not yet know the sale price of RFA Diligence. In August 2016 the Disposal Services Authority advertised a competition for the sale of the former RFA Diligence for future use. This competition has not reached the stage where formal commercial bids have been received.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-10-25T15:38:24.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603974/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603974/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603974/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-17","RFA Diligence","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the sale of RFA Diligence will amount to, or exceed, the amount of taxpayer-funded expenditure of £16 million that was spent on refitting the vessel to extend its life to 2020.","false","Biography information for Lord Touhig",,"Lord Touhig","HL2370"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603975","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-26","<p>I have reflected on the concerns raised by the noble and gallant Lord, Lord Boyce, regarding the sale of Royal Fleet Auxiliary Diligence.</p><p>The Royal Navy continues to work with industry and is investing to ensure that Service personnel have the required skills in diagnostics and repair to provide this future support. More widely, consideration of different and innovative ways of providing that support to deliver the best value for money for the taxpayer is an ongoing process. The Royal Navy is confident that, through a combination of the measures that I outlined in response to the oral question by Lord Boyce on 13 September 2016, the required support will be available.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-10-26T15:05:25.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603975/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603975/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603975/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-17","RFA Diligence","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by Earl Howe on 13 September (HL Deb, col 1389), whether, and if so when, they are planning to provide an update regarding the concerns raised by Lord Boyce.","false","Biography information for Lord Touhig",,"Lord Touhig","HL2371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603976","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-26","<p>Should on-board engineers be unable to resolve a problem with any ship or submarine, there is a range of ways in which operational maintenance and repair can be delivered. This can include the deployment of a Royal Navy repair and maintenance party, or utilising well-established commercial arrangements and international agreements, such as the use of other countries' bases and facilities. This is particularly the case where resources and facilities are not available within the Ministry of Defence or are more effectively provided by a third party.</p>",,"Earl Howe","HL2369","2016-10-26T15:08:00.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603976/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603976/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603976/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-10-17","RFA Diligence","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by Earl Howe on 13 September (HL Deb, col 1389), when a Royal Navy vessel requires repair and on-board engineers are unable to resolve the problem without the help of other, more specialist, engineers how this will be achieved without the support of RFA Diligence.","false","Biography information for Lord Touhig",,"Lord Touhig","HL2372"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603977","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-10-31","<p>The government has not made such an estimate. Such estimates are made, only where necessary, to assist in the assessment of specific policy proposals.</p><p>Part B (Fire safety) of the Building Regulations for England was last subjected to a major review in 2006. Since then the guidance has been subject to minor amendments in 2007, 2010 and 2013. Where substantive changes were made, in 2006 and 2013, the government of the day issued an impact assessment which set out the matters that were considered at the time. These documents ( attached) are available in the library of the house and available on the internet at;</p><p><a href="http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20120919132719/http:/www.communities.gov.uk/publications/planningandbuilding/regulatoryimpactassessment10" target="_blank">http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20120919132719/http://www.communities.gov.uk/publications/planningandbuilding/regulatoryimpactassessment10</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/39372/121128_-_Part_B_IA_-_to_publish_for_web.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/39372/121128_-_Part_B_IA_-_to_publish_for_web.pdf</a></p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","HL2374","2016-10-31T17:01:42.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603977/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603977/answer","161031 RIA Changes to Part B of the Building - HL2373 & HL2374.pdf ; 161031 Simplifying the provisions of par B2 of the building regulations  - HL2373 & 2374.pdf","161031 RIA Changes to Part B of the Building - HL2373 & HL2374.pdf ; 161031 Simplifying the provisions of par B2 of the building regulations  - HL2373 & 2374.pdf","Regulatory impact assessment ; Part B2 of the Building regulation","Regulatory impact assessment ; Part B2 of the Building regulation","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603977/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-17","Fire Regulations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they considered the economic, societal and environmental impacts of fire when producing the Approved Document B (fire safety) regulations; and if not why not; and whether they consider that the Building Act 1984 and the Sustainable and Secure Building Act 2004 provide that the purposes for which regulations may be made for the design, construction, servicing and fittings of buildings should include such impacts.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL2373"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603978","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-10-31","<p>The government has not made such an estimate. Such estimates are made, only where necessary, to assist in the assessment of specific policy proposals.</p><p>Part B (Fire safety) of the Building Regulations for England was last subjected to a major review in 2006. Since then the guidance has been subject to minor amendments in 2007, 2010 and 2013. Where substantive changes were made, in 2006 and 2013, the government of the day issued an impact assessment which set out the matters that were considered at the time. These documents ( attached) are available in the library of the house and available on the internet at;</p><p><a href="http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20120919132719/http:/www.communities.gov.uk/publications/planningandbuilding/regulatoryimpactassessment10" target="_blank">http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20120919132719/http://www.communities.gov.uk/publications/planningandbuilding/regulatoryimpactassessment10</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/39372/121128_-_Part_B_IA_-_to_publish_for_web.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/39372/121128_-_Part_B_IA_-_to_publish_for_web.pdf</a></p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","HL2373","2016-10-31T17:01:42.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603978/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603978/answer","161031 RIA Changes to Part B of the Building - HL2373 & HL2374.pdf ; 161031 Simplifying the provisions of par B2 of the building regulations  - HL2373 & 2374.pdf","161031 RIA Changes to Part B of the Building - HL2373 & HL2374.pdf ; 161031 Simplifying the provisions of par B2 of the building regulations  - HL2373 & 2374.pdf","Regulatory impact assessment ; Part B2 of the Building regulation","Regulatory impact assessment ; Part B2 of the Building regulation","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603978/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-17","Buildings: Fires","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of the economic and environmental costs of fire in domestic, industrial and commercial buildings, and, if such estimates have not been made, why not.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL2374"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603979","Department of Health","false","2016-10-31","<p>We have made no such assessment.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-10-31T13:27:46.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603979/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603979/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603979/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-17","Alcoholic Drinks: Misuse","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of why the estimated number of English hospital admissions relating to alcohol consumption has doubled between 2004/05, when the Licensing Act 2003 entered into force, and 2014/15.","false","Biography information for Lord Brooke of Alverthorpe",,"Lord Brooke of Alverthorpe","HL2375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603980","Department of Health","false","2016-10-31","<p>The new <em>UK Chief Medical Officers’ Low Risk Drinking Guidelines</em> provide the public with the most up to date scientific information to help people make informed decisions about their own drinking. A copy of the guidelines is attached.</p><p> </p><p>The Department and Public Health England (PHE) will be reviewing the advice on higher risk drinking, in light of the new guidelines, at a United Kingdom level through a consensus process in partnership with the Devolved Administrations.</p><p> </p><p>PHE is using its <em>One You </em>campaign to motivate people to take steps to improve their health through tackling the main risk factors such as smoking, inactivity, obesity, and alcohol. <em>One You </em>provides a Drinks Tracker app to help drinkers identify risky behaviour and lower their alcohol consumption.</p><p> </p><p>Local government has been given the responsibility to improve people’s health. This includes responsibility for tackling problem drinking and commissioning appropriate prevention and treatment services for their local population’s needs. Over the next five years, we will invest more than £16 billion in local government public health services.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England’s <em>NHS Five Year Forward View</em> commits the National Health Service to support national action on alcohol. The National Commissioning for Quality and Innovation (CQUIN) payments framework was set up in 2009-10 to encourage services providers to continually improve the quality of care provided to patients and to achieve transparency. To help deliver their commitment to reduce harmful alcohol consumption NHS England has published a CQUIN to incentivise interventions to reduce risky behaviours, and prevent ill health through alcohol and tobacco consumption. This has a number of components, including alcohol screening, brief advice and referral to specialist services.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-10-31T14:48:44.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603980/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603980/answer","HL2376 - UK CMOs Low Risk Drinking Guidelines.pdf","HL2376 - UK CMOs Low Risk Drinking Guidelines.pdf","CMO Low Risk Drinking Guidelines","CMO Low Risk Drinking Guidelines","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603980/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-17","Alcoholic Drinks: Misuse","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what new action they propose to take to halt and reverse the upward trend in the number of English hospital admissions relating to alcohol consumption, and who will be responsible and accountable for the implementation of such actions.","false","Biography information for Lord Brooke of Alverthorpe",,"Lord Brooke of Alverthorpe","HL2376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603981","Department of Health","false","2016-10-31","<p>Figures of the cost to the National Health Service of alcohol misuse are not available on an annual basis.</p><p> </p><p>The most recent estimate from Public Health England (PHE) for 2014 is that alcohol costs the NHS around £3.5 billion per annum. The Department estimates that just under half of that is due to alcohol related inpatient admissions to hospital. This information is available in the public domain, as evidenced by PHE’s report <em>Alcohol and drugs prevention, treatment and recovery: why invest?, Public Health England</em>. A copy is attached.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-10-31T14:50:37.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603981/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603981/answer","HL2377 - why-invest-2014-alcohol-and-drugs.pdf","HL2377 - why-invest-2014-alcohol-and-drugs.pdf","PHE Alcohol and Drugs Prevention","PHE Alcohol and Drugs Prevention","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/603981/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-10-17","Alcoholic Drinks: Misuse","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what the estimated cost of hospital admissions relating to alcohol consumption was for the NHS in (1) 2004/05 and (2) 2014/15.","false","Biography information for Lord Brooke of Alverthorpe",,"Lord Brooke of Alverthorpe","HL2377"
