"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604214","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-20","<p>My rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy has not had any discussions with my rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State for International Development on weather-indexed insurance in the last six months.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-10-20T14:49:28.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604214/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604214/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604214/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-10-17","Developing Countries: Weather","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent discussions he has had with the Department for International Development on the UK's commitment to weather-indexed insurance.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","48994"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604215","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-20","<p>The UK’s support to African Risk Capacity (ARC), the Caribbean Catastrophe Risk Insurance Facility (CCRIF) and the Pacific Catastrophe Risk Assessment and Financing Initiative (PCRAFI) is managed by the Department for International Development (DFID).</p><p>In December 2015, every G7 nation set out how they will meet a collective target to reach an additional 400 million people with risk insurance by 2020. The UK has led the way, making excellent progress in delivering on its pledges of support for Climate Risk Insurance in the past year including funding for ARC and PCRAFI. UK Ministers have been invited to participate in side events at the Marrakesh Conference of Parties (COP) meeting to highlight progress with the G7’s InsuResilience climate risk insurance initiative and on ARC.</p><p>Currently, just 5% of losses from natural disasters in low-income countries are covered by insurance (against around 40% in developed countries), leaving millions with nothing to rebuild their lives after disaster strikes. UK initiatives give countries and people the tools they need to get themselves back on their feet, which is firmly in our national interest.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-20T16:48:49.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604215/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604215/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604215/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-17","Climate Change Convention: Morocco","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what plans her Department has made to publicise Government support for the (a) African Risk Capacity, (b) Catastrophe Risk Insurance Facility and (c) Pacific Catastrophe Risk Assessment and Financing Initiative at the Marrakesh Climate Conference, to be held in November 2016.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","48995"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604216","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-20","<p>Protecting those who are vulnerable to loss and damage due to climate change includes responding to disasters, helping people adapt to climate change and reducing greenhouse gas emissions to keep global warming to manageable levels.</p><p>The UK Government has committed to increase the UK’s climate finance by at least 50%, and will provide £5.8 billion over the next 5 years, of which half will be focused on helping people adapt to climate change including the most vulnerable. We have also committed to contributing to the G7 InsuResilience target of an additional 400 million people gaining access to insurance by 2020. The UK is actively engaged on these issues within the United Nations, including through its seat on the Executive Committee that is responsible for guiding action on loss and damage.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-10-20T14:26:12.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604216/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604216/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604216/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-17","Climate Change Convention: Morocco","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what proposals the Government plans to put forward at the Marrakesh Climate Change Conference in November 2016 to try to protect people who are most vulnerable to loss and damage caused by climate change.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","48992"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604217","Department for International Development","false","2016-10-20","<p>The UK is proud to be a global leader in disaster risk finance and insurance and we are committed to contributing to meeting the G7’s InsuResilience collective target (set out in the 2015 G7 Leaders Elmau declaration) of helping up to an additional 400 million people in the most vulnerable developing countries to gain access to climate risk insurance by 2020. The Department for International Development (DFID) leads the delivery of the Government’s plans to scale up the use of insurance and risk finance instruments in developing countries to enable:</p><ul><li>Increased resilience for millions of the most vulnerable people, through improved access to insurance cover,</li><li>Faster, more efficient emergency response, with a larger proportion of losses in vulnerable developing countries to be covered by insurance systems, taking the strain off the overstretched humanitarian system,</li><li>Stronger and more stable economic development in developing countries, by helping to reduce the costs and barriers to credit.</li></ul>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-10-20T16:47:36.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604217/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604217/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604217/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-10-17","Climate Change Convention: Morocco","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the potential merits of the Government's support for climate risk insurance as part of her preparations for the COP22 UN Climate Change Summit in Marrakesh, to be held in November 2016.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","48993"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604218","Department for Education","false","2016-10-24","<p>Department for Education officials hold regular discussions with their counterparts in the devolved administrations to consider the implications of the apprenticeship levy on their own apprenticeship programmes and for cross-border employers.</p><p> </p><p>We want to ensure that apprenticeship funding works for employers and learners, wherever they are in the UK.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2016-10-24T16:02:24.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604218/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604218/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604218/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-10-17","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what discussions she has had with devolved administrations on the operation of the Apprenticeship Levy.","false","Biography information for Danny Kinahan","South Antrim","Danny Kinahan","48935"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604219","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-25","<p>We recognise the need for a smooth transition as the UK leaves the EU which minimises disruption to our trading relationships. Ministers and officials in the Department for International Trade are working closely with counterparts across a wide range of markets in order to promote the UK as a great place to do business and with which to trade. We are taking advantage of all the opportunities available to us to ensure that Britain becomes the global leader in free trade once we leave the EU.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-10-25T10:50:42.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604219/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604219/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604219/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-17","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, with which countries the UK has initiated negotiations on possible bilateral trade agreements.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","48884"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604221","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-25","<p>The Government is currently reviewing its trade policy as the UK prepares to leave the EU. This offers us an opportunity to forge a new role for ourselves in the world: to negotiate and design, in time, our own trade arrangements. The UK remains committed to ensuring developing countries can reduce poverty through trading opportunities.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","48831 ; 48832","2016-10-25T10:36:34.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604221/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604221/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604221/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-17","Developing Countries: Import Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, if he will eliminate import tariffs on agricultural produce from developing nations when the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","48830"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604222","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-25","<p>The Government is currently reviewing its trade policy as the UK prepares to leave the EU. This offers us an opportunity to forge a new role for ourselves in the world: to negotiate and design, in time, our own trade arrangements. The UK remains committed to ensuring developing countries can reduce poverty through trading opportunities.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","48830 ; 48832","2016-10-25T10:36:34.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604222/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604222/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604222/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-17","Developing Countries: Import Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, if he will eliminate the import tariffs on all unprocessed fruit and vegetables from developing nations when the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","48831"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604223","Department for International Trade","false","2016-10-25","<p>The Government is currently reviewing its trade policy as the UK prepares to leave the EU. This offers us an opportunity to forge a new role for ourselves in the world: to negotiate and design, in time, our own trade arrangements. The UK remains committed to ensuring developing countries can reduce poverty through trading opportunities.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","48830 ; 48831","2016-10-25T10:36:34.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604223/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604223/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604223/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-10-17","Developing Countries: Import Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, if he will eliminate the import tariffs on canned goods from developing nations when the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","48832"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604224","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-20","<p>We want to continue to attract the brightest and the best to the UK after exit. UK researchers can still apply for Horizon 2020 projects, with the certainty that any funding will be guaranteed by the UK Government for the cycle of the programme. The government has recently announced that EU students applying for a place at an English university or further education institution in the 2017 to 2018 academic year will continue to be eligible for student loans and grants – and will be for the duration of their course. The Prime Minister has been clear that during negotiations she wants to protect the status of EU nationals already living here, and the only circumstances in which that would not be possible is if British citizens’ rights in European member states were not protected in return.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2016-10-20T15:58:28.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604224/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604224/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604224/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-17","Higher Education: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Answer of 13 October 2016 to Question 47818, what the Government's policy is on changes to the rights of UK universities and their students and staff from other EU countries.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","48877"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604225","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-20","<p>The Prime Minister has been clear we will not give a running commentary on our EU exit negotiations. We will ensure that we engage closely with all relevant interlocutors.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-10-20T16:28:50.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604225/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604225/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604225/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-17","Department for Exiting the European Union: Visits Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what overseas visits he has made since his appointment.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","48919"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604226","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-20","<p>Legislation resulting from the UK’s exit must work for the whole of the United Kingdom. The Prime Minister has already held initial conversations with the leaders of the devolved Governments about our plans, and she will make sure that the devolved Administrations have every opportunity to work closely with us.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-10-20T13:42:37.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604226/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604226/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604226/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-17","Immigration: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what recent discussions he has had with stakeholders in the UK on devolution of control over immigration to the Scottish Parliament once the UK leave the EU.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","49003"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604227","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-25","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union has engaged with a wide range of organisations including Universities UK, the Royal Academies and the pharmaceutical sector, as well as colleagues from the Department for Education and the Department of Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy.</p><p>The Prime Minister has been clear that she is determined to protect the status of EU nationals already living here, and the only circumstances in which that would not be possible is if British citizens’ rights in European member states were not protected in return.</p><p>The UK remains fully open to scientists and researchers from across the EU. We highly value the contribution of EU and international staff, and there are no immediate changes to their rights to live and work in the UK.</p><p>The announcement on underwriting Horizon 2020 funding underlines our commitment to do what is necessary to maintain the UK as an attractive place to conduct research and innovation.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2016-10-25T11:32:56.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604227/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604227/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/604227/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-17","Migrant Workers: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what recent discussions he has had with his Ministerial colleagues on the legal status of foreign scientific researchers resident in the UK following the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Mr Richard Bacon","South Norfolk","Mr Richard Bacon","49007"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606038","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-10-20","<p>Immigration is a reserved matter. However, we are working closely with the Scottish Government and we will get the best possible deal for all parts of the United Kingdom as we leave the EU. We will give the Scottish Government every opportunity to have their say as we develop the negotiating strategy.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-10-20T15:03:33.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606038/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606038/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/606038/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-10-17","Immigration: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, if he will devolve control over immigration to the Scottish Government as part of his negotiations on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Owen Thompson","Midlothian","Owen Thompson","906710"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601905","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-24","HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) does not hold data on the number of tax credit cases awaiting consideration by Concentrix broken down specifically by constituency areas. HMRC is currently focused on resolving the outstanding cases but will be preparing analysis, which will be made available in due course.","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-10-24T14:57:13.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601905/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601905/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601905/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-14","Concentrix: Kingston upon Hull","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 15 September 2016 to Question 46636, on Concentrix, if he will provide that same information for (a) Kingston upon Hull North constituency and (b) Hull City Council.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","48715"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601906","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-24","<p>As set out by the Chancellor, the Treasury will guarantee funding for structural and investment fund projects and funding secured through direct bids to the European Commission, even after the UK leaves the EU. This is where the funding provides strong value for money and is in line with domestic strategic priorities. These include projects signed after Autumn Statement and before we leave the EU.</p><p> </p><p>Alongside this funding, the Start-Up loan programme, funded by the UK government and overseen by the British Business Bank (BBB), has supported over 39,500 entrepreneurs to set up their own business and facilitated loans of over £230m.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-10-24T13:11:55.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601906/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601906/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601906/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-14","New Businesses: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he plans to substitute funding to start-up loan schemes previously funded completely or partly by EU programmes after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","48725"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601907","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-19","<p>From April 2017 the government will introduce a levy to fund the step change needed to achieve 3 million apprenticeship starts and an uplift in their quality by 2020. The systems required to implement this in time for April 2017 are on track and are being tested on a regular basis. This includes progress by both HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC), with regards to the collection of the levy, and from the Skills Funding Agency who are building the digital accounts for employers to access levy funds.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Education has issued guidance for employers regarding the apprenticeship levy. Further guidance, confirming the funding policy, will be published shortly. HMRC has also issued guidance to software developers to ensure that employers’ payroll systems are ready for the apprenticeship levy and will publish further guidance for employers in December.</p><p> </p><p>The government have been working with employers and training providers since the concept of the apprenticeship levy was introduced to ensure that it works for them. These conversations have played a major part in shaping how the apprenticeship levy will work and we will continue these discussions to assist employers and providers as they prepare for the introduction of the levy.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-10-19T11:07:22.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601907/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601907/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601907/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-14","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of the timeframe to implement the Apprenticeship Levy; and what steps he is taking to ensure that businesses affected by the levy are given adequate time to make adjustments.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","48753"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601908","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-24","<p>The Seed Enterprise Investment Scheme, Enterprise Investment Scheme and Venture Capital Trusts scheme provide tax reliefs to encourage individuals to invest in early stage, higher risk companies that would otherwise struggle to access finance. The government has no plans to withdraw these tax reliefs.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-10-24T14:54:27.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601908/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601908/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601908/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-14","New Businesses: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of reducing Government tax incentives in the tech start-up sector in order to reduce the number of companies potentially unable to attract private investment after tax reliefs expire.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","48773"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601909","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-24","<p>The Government agrees that it is important for consumers to have access to a diverse range of investment choices and for start-ups and SMEs to have access to a wide range of funding sources.</p><p> </p><p>To this end, the Government has implemented a proportionate regime for peer-to-peer lending and crowdfunding that gives retail investors the opportunity to invest in start-ups and SMEs. Retail investors can also benefit from other initiatives, including Undertakings for Collective Investments in Transferrable Securities, where the fund can allocate up to 10% of assets to venture capital.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has no plans to review the definition of sophisticated investors as set out in the Financial Promotions Order 2005.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-10-24T14:59:50.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601909/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601909/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601909/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-14","New Businesses: Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of lowering the qualification for investors in the start-up sector in order to grant lower net worth individuals more freedom to invest.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","48774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601910","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-10-24","<p>Business rates are based on valuations from the Valuation Office Agency and we do not intervene in their independent assessments. We have proposed a £3.4 billion transitional relief scheme to ensure that no ratepayer is unfairly penalised by the 2017 revaluation.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-10-24T15:49:32.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601910/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601910/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601910/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-14","Non-domestic Rates: Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will amend his policy on proposed increases to business rates in order to help augment the speed of broadband roll-out.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","48776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601911","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-10-24","<p>We are working to assess the effect of the decision to leave the EU on all parts of the UK digital sector. Tech City UK has been successful in supporting the growth of thriving digital clusters across the UK and they are an important partner in ensuring that we continue to support the sector as we prepare to leave the EU. We are drawing on their insight into the needs of digital businesses and start-ups across the UK to help ensure we get the best deal for the future of the digital sector, and for the wider economy.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-10-24T09:20:18.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601911/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601911/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601911/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-10-14","Tech City UK","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment she has made of the effect of the UK leaving the EU on her policy on Tech City UK.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","48777"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601912","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-24","<p>All crowdfunding platforms fall within the FCA’s definition of regulated investments and are therefore subject to FCA rules. These rules require companies to maintain effective systems and controls to address the risk that they might be exploited by criminals. Where a firm’s systems and controls are not adequate, the FCA can and does take enforcement action.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2016-10-24T13:16:48.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601912/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601912/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601912/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-14","Crowdfunding: Money Laundering","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make an assessment of the dangers of money laundering being undertaken by means of anonymous online crowdfunding investment platforms.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","48778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601913","HM Treasury","false","2016-10-24","<p>E-cigarettes are not liable for excise duty as they do not include tobacco. However, they are still liable for VAT.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-10-24T14:49:01.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601913/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601913/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601913/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-10-14","Taxation: Electronic Cigarettes","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of reducing taxes on e-cigarettes on health grounds.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","48783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601914","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-03-06","<p>The three Government approved Tenancy Deposit Schemes in England help ensure that tenants are treated fairly at the end of their tenancy through protecting deposits.</p><p>A deposit can be protected in a custodial scheme where the deposit is paid (submitted) and held by the scheme until the end of the tenancy. The scheme will pay the deposit back (return) to the tenant if they have fulfilled all their obligations at the end of the tenancy. A deposit can also be protected in an insured scheme, where the landlord or agent holds the deposit and pays it back to the tenant at the end of the tenancy. The deposit is not submitted to or returned by the scheme.</p><p>The figures available for the number of deposits protected for tenants in Greater London since 2011, are set out in Table 1, and for deposits submitted and returned in Table 2.</p><p>Table 1 – tenant’s deposits protected in Greater London</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Total number of deposits protected</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>434,031</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>398,635</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>453,200</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>499,098</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>545,937</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Table 2 – tenant’s deposits submitted and returned in Greater London</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Number of deposits submitted</p></td><td><p>Number of deposits returned</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>74,202</p></td><td><p>55,550</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>77,709</p></td><td><p>62,341</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>82,613</p></td><td><p>67,583</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>88,465</p></td><td><p>70,105</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>90,849</p></td><td><p>76,305</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>The differences between the number of deposits submitted and returned are due to different lengths of tenancies, cases going through the dispute resolution process, and the protection of more deposits as the private rental market continues to grow.</p><p>Overall, 98 per cent of all deposits protected in England since the launch of the tenancy deposit scheme in 2007, are returned to the tenant at the end of their tenancy.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell","48710 ; 48728","2017-03-06T14:29:41.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601914/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601914/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/601914/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-10-14","Tenancy Deposit Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to the Answer of 16 November 2015 to Question 13604, what proportion of the deposits handed back in each of the schemes and for each of the years listed in the Table of Adjudications were subject to adjudication by their respective deposit protection scheme.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","48727"
